<p style = "padding: 30px"> <font size = 5>&emsp;<b>Groupthink</b><br>
    &emsp;Groupthink is one of the most common ways that the decision making process of groups can be disrupted. Groupthink is when members of a group will agree with the ideas that come at them and minimize conflict in order to try and achieve perceived cohesion or speed to try and reach a deadline or goal. This comes at the harm of the group&#39;s goals, as blindly agreeing with ideas will cause you to make worse decisions. We can see this sort of effect illustrated in NASA&#39;s Challenger launch in 1986 or in the Pearl Harbor attack in 1941, as both situations involve groupthink causing complacency, resulting in disaster. This can be avoided in the Mood and Grasp Graph by giving ourselves time to work and not putting ourselves under pressure with time constraints, as logical errors could appear. Also, we could play devil&#39;s advocate with our ideas to objectively test their merit.
    

